Here is an example of a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <boost/optional.hpp>

namespace markdown {

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Define a mapping from Markdown syntax to HTML
    static const std::unordered_map<std::string, std::string> replacements = {
        {"# ", "<h1>"},
        {"## ", "<h2>"},
        {"### ", "<h3>"},
        {"#### ", "<h4>"},
        {"__", "<i>"},
        {"**", "<b>"},
        {"[", "<a"],
        {"(", "["),
        {"[", "<a href="],
        {"}", "</a>"],
        {"](", "]("},
        {"`,",_tD`},
        {">", "</td>`},
        {"</tr","</tr>`},
        {"\"", ""}],
        {"``", "<code>"},
        {"```", "</code>"},
    };

    std::string html;
    boost::optional<std::string> inTag;

    for (char c : markdown) {
        if (c == '(' || c == '[' || c == '`' || c == '`' || c == '%' || c == '*') {
            inTag = std::string(1, c);
        } else if (inTag && c == inTag.get()[0]) {
            inTag.reset();
        } else {
            if (inTag) {
                html += inTag.get();
            }

            for (const auto& [markdown, htmlReplacement] : replacements) {
                if (markdown.find(c) == 0 && markdown.size() == 1) {
                    html += htmlReplacement;
                    break;
                }
            }

            html += c;
        }
    }

    if (inTag) {
        html += inTag.get();
    }

    return html;
}

} // namespace markdown

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello **Markdown**!";
    std::string html = markdown::markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;  // Output: "<h1>Hello <b>Markdown</b>!</h1>"

    return 0;
}

```

This function uses an unordered map to replace Markdown syntax with HTML. It also handles the cases where Markdown syntax spans multiple characters (like links and code blocks).

Please note that this is a simplified version of Markdown transformation and there might be some corner cases where it may fail to transform correctly. Additional validation is necessary for more complex transformations.

References:

* [Markdown Syntax](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax)
* [HTML Syntax](https://www.w3schools.com/html/html_elements.asp)

Also, keep in mind that Boost::optional can be replaced with std::optional once you're using a C++17 compliant compiler.

Lastly, error handling is not added for brevity, but you would want to add proper error handling for edge cases.

